charmed_rust-wsu: Standardize Error Handling with thiserror

# Objective
Add proper error chaining support across all charmed_rust error types using thiserror's `#[from]` and `#[source]` attributes. This enables full error cause chains and improves debugging.

# Requirements

## 1. Understanding #[from] vs #[source]

```rust
use thiserror::Error;

#[derive(Error, Debug)]
pub enum Error {
    // #[from] = automatic From impl + source chain
    // Use when you want: other_error.into() or ? operator
    #[error("io error")]
    Io(#[from] std::io::Error),

    // #[source] = source chain only, no From impl
    // Use when you need to add context
    #[error("failed to read config from {path}")]
    ConfigRead {
        path: String,
        #[source]
        source: std::io::Error,
    },

    // #[source] with Box for trait objects
    #[error("underlying error")]
    Underlying(#[source] Box<dyn std::error::Error + Send + Sync>),
}
```

## 2. Cross-Crate Error Chaining
Implement error wrapping between charmed crates:

```rust
// In bubbletea::Error
#[derive(Error, Debug)]
pub enum Error {
    #[error("io error")]
    Io(#[from] std::io::Error),

    // Wrap lipgloss errors with context
    #[error("style rendering failed")]
    Style(#[source] lipgloss::Error),
}

// In huh::FormError  
#[derive(Error, Debug)]
pub enum FormError {
    // Wrap bubbletea errors
    #[error("program execution failed")]
    Program(#[source] bubbletea::Error),

    // Wrap validation with context
    #[error("field '{field}' validation failed")]
    Validation {
        field: String,
        #[source]
        source: Box<dyn std::error::Error + Send + Sync>,
    },
}

// In wish::Error
#[derive(Error, Debug)]
pub enum Error {
    #[error("io error")]
    Io(#[from] std::io::Error),

    // Chain from bubbletea for SSH TUI apps
    #[error("tui error")]
    Tui(#[source] bubbletea::Error),
}
```

## 3. Error Chain Traversal

```rust
// Users can traverse the error chain:
fn handle_error(err: &wish::Error) {
    // Print full chain
    let mut source = err.source();
    while let Some(cause) = source {
        eprintln!("  caused by: {}", cause);
        source = cause.source();
    }
}

// Or use anyhow for automatic chain display:
fn main() -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    run_app()?; // Automatically shows full chain on error
    Ok(())
}
```

